                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d370">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.94/1502a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-05-08T16:00:00-04:00"
                            >May 8, 1940—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>144. The Department’s telegram 142, May 4, 2 p.m., was sent to you after
                    consultation with and at the desire of the President.</p>
                <p>2. We understand that the President approved Mr. Sayre’s making a visit to Japan
                    and while there conferring with you and, if he so desired, making courtesy calls
                    on Japanese officials. There was no thought here that Sayre should or would
                    embark upon discussion with Japanese officials of any subject of high policy. We
                    are at a loss to understand why he did so and thus became involved in
                    discussions which are appropriate only to our diplomatic representation. We
                    regard as especially unfortunate the development of approach and necessary
                    rejection which took place in the final conversation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
